  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>She is thirty-eight years old. She runs three mornings a week, doesn't smoke, has never had high cholesterol, and before today had no particular reason to think about her heart. She walked into the emergency department on her own. The triage nurse notes her blood pressure and her chief complaint: chest tightness, trouble breathing, nausea. The attending considers reflux. He considers a panic attack. She is young, she has no risk factors, and he has seen a lot of anxious women. He orders an ECG. It comes back with subtle changes. He orders a troponin. The first one returns borderline. He waits. While he waits, one of her coronary arteries is tearing.</p>
</section>

<section id="not-atherosclerosis" class="reveal">
  <h2>A different kind of heart attack</h2>
  <p>The condition is called spontaneous coronary artery dissection — SCAD — and it has nothing to do with the heart attack medicine was built to find. There is no plaque. No decades of accumulated cholesterol. No slow ruin of bad habits catching up. Instead, the wall of a coronary artery simply splits. Blood forces itself between the vessel's layers, forming a hidden hematoma that compresses the artery from within. The lumen narrows. Blood flow drops. Cardiac muscle begins to die. The mechanism is entirely distinct from atherosclerosis — and the distinction matters, because the protocols designed to catch one reliably miss the other.</p>
  <p>SCAD was first described in 1931, in a British Medical Journal case report about a 42-year-old woman who collapsed and died of sudden chest pain. At autopsy, her right coronary artery had ruptured. The authors noted the finding and moved on. For the better part of the next eight decades, the medical literature treated SCAD as a curiosity — rare, peripartum, almost universally fatal, barely worth a dedicated research program. All three characterizations were wrong. The condition accounts for roughly a third of all heart attacks in women under fifty, according to a 2024 npj Cardiovascular Health review, though some older studies estimated lower prevalence (e.g., 1-4% in general MI populations per 2012 JACC data), potentially due to underdiagnosis or differing diagnostic criteria. It is the leading cause of cardiac emergency in pregnancy and the postpartum period. The majority of cases, though, occur in neither pregnant women nor women under forty — they occur in otherwise healthy women between forty-five and fifty-three who have, by every standard metric the ER uses to assess cardiac risk, nothing wrong with them.</p>
</section>

<section id="wrong-patient" class="reveal">
  <h2>The checklist was never built to catch her</h2>
  <p>When a sixty-two-year-old man with type 2 diabetes and a forty-pack-year smoking history walks into an ER clutching his chest, the system moves. Appropriately. The machinery of modern cardiac emergency care — the twelve-lead, the serial troponins, the cath lab on standby — was built around him. The clinical trials that established the protocols enrolled men who looked like him. His presentation matches the mental model inscribed into every attending physician in every emergency department in the country. The model works. For him.</p>
  <p>SCAD is not associated with high cholesterol. Not with smoking. Not with diabetes, obesity, sedentary living, or family history of atherosclerotic disease. The women who develop it are often, by the numbers, healthier than average. Some are endurance athletes. Some have just given birth. Some experienced an intense emotional stressor — a death, a trauma, an extended period of extreme psychological pressure — in the days before the tear. None of that appears on the standard cardiac risk checklist.</p>
  <p>So when she walks in struggling to breathe, the checklist says: low risk. The checklist is not wrong to flag that. It was just never built to catch her.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"We listen less well to women. We are much more likely to associate their symptoms with psychological causes." — Dr. Sharonne Hayes, Mayo Clinic</p></aside>

<section id="symptom-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The symptoms that explain themselves away</h2>
  <p>SCAD doesn't arrive with the crushing substernal pain of a textbook MI. Its calling cards are shortness of breath, nausea, jaw pain, back pain, light-headedness — a pressure that patients often describe as tightness rather than agony. These are also, in a young woman without cardiac risk factors, precisely the symptoms most likely to be attributed to something else. Anxiety disorder. Panic attack. Gastroesophageal reflux. Musculoskeletal strain. The differential diagnosis for SCAD, in a young healthy woman, reads like a list of things doctors tell young women they probably have.</p>
  <p>Then the tests seem to confirm it. Early ECGs in SCAD can appear normal, or show only subtle changes that fall short of the threshold that triggers alarm. Initial troponin levels — the standard blood marker for heart muscle damage — can return borderline or negative in the first hours, because ischemia depends on how much of the artery is compressed and for how long. The tests designed to rule in a heart attack can rule it out. The patient is sent home. She comes back by ambulance.</p>
  <p>This is documented. Not anecdotally, not through patient advocacy networks, but in peer-reviewed cardiology literature. A 2023 review in <em>The Journal of Emergency Medicine</em> described SCAD as "the great mimicker" in emergency settings — young, female, no risk factors, symptoms attributed to non-cardiac causes, diagnosis delayed. The delay that follows isn't incidental. It's the mechanism of harm.</p>
</section>

<section id="aha-statement" class="reveal">
  <h2>The statement that changed nothing</h2>
  <p>In 2018, the American Heart Association—whose research and guidelines receive funding from pharmaceutical companies like Pfizer and AstraZeneca—published a landmark scientific statement on SCAD in <em>Circulation</em>. The writing group included cardiologists from Mayo Clinic, Massachusetts General Hospital, and institutions across Europe and North America. The statement was unambiguous: SCAD is an underdiagnosed cause of myocardial infarction, especially in young women; diagnosis requires a high index of suspicion precisely because patients lack traditional risk factors; initial testing can be misleadingly normal; and, most critically, treating SCAD like atherosclerotic disease can make it worse.</p>
  <p>That last point is counterintuitive enough to need stating directly. The reflex response to a blocked coronary artery is to stent it open. In atherosclerotic disease, where a plaque has ruptured and the vessel is obstructed, this works. In SCAD, the artery wall is already compromised — the problem is a hematoma within the vessel wall, not a clot in the lumen. Forcing a stent into that vessel risks propagating the dissection further. The AHA statement recommends conservative management for most stable SCAD patients: antiplatelet therapy, beta-blockers, close monitoring, and allowing the artery to heal on its own. Which it often does, within weeks. This is not doing nothing. It is doing the right thing for the right diagnosis. A physician who doesn't know the patient has SCAD, and reflexively applies the atherosclerotic protocol, may cause harm in the act of trying to help.</p>
  <p>"Even with what we have learned over the past several years," said Dr. Sharonne Hayes — chair of the AHA writing group and founder of Mayo Clinic's Women's Heart Clinic — "SCAD continues to be misdiagnosed and underdiagnosed. And we know it is not rare. It is the number one cause of heart attack during pregnancy and the number one cause of heart attack in women under age 50."</p>
  <p>That was seven years ago. The statement remains available to every cardiologist with an internet connection. SCAD remains underdiagnosed.</p>
</section>

<section id="structural-failure" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why a published paper doesn't fix this</h2>
  <p>It would be more satisfying if there were a villain. There isn't. The failure here is cognitive and structural — baked into medical training that prioritizes male-centric trial data and resists updates, allowing misdiagnoses to persist despite clear evidence from the AHA statement.</p>
  <p>Emergency medicine was constructed around a cardiac template derived from clinical trials that, for decades, underenrolled or simply excluded women. The canonical heart attack patient, in the model that trained generations of physicians, is older, male, and risk-factor-laden. That model works exceptionally well for the patient it was designed for. It becomes a liability when applied as a universal.</p>
  <p>Cognitive biases in medicine are not moral failures. Anchoring — fixating on an initial diagnosis and interpreting subsequent evidence through that frame — is documented in expert decision-making under pressure, not a character flaw. Availability bias — reaching for the diagnosis you've seen most recently and most often — is universal. For young women in the ER, the initial anchor is almost invariably non-cardiac. She's young. She has no risk factors. She seems frightened. The diagnostic path narrows before the tests come back.</p>
  <p>"We listen less well to women," Dr. Hayes has said. "We are much more likely to associate their symptoms with psychological causes." This isn't a tentative opinion. It's a finding, replicated across the literature on sex differences in cardiac care, and it has specific consequences: a heart attack in a young woman is more likely to be fatal than in a young man, in part because her symptoms are more often attributed to her psychology before they're attributed to her heart. A 2024 review in <em>npj Cardiovascular Health</em> found that SCAD accounts for around twenty percent of all acute coronary syndrome presentations in women under sixty. Not a footnote. A fifth of all heart attacks in that population. Still frequently overlooked.</p>
</section>

<section id="fmd-connection" class="reveal">
  <h2>The predisposition hiding in plain sight</h2>
  <p>The "she seemed fine" dismissal is particularly damning given what research has uncovered about SCAD's biology. Fibromuscular dysplasia — FMD — is a non-atherosclerotic, non-inflammatory condition marked by abnormal cell growth in arterial walls. It has been identified in approximately seventy percent of SCAD patients across large contemporary cohorts; studies using comprehensive head-to-pelvis imaging push the number higher. FMD is not a new discovery. It was first described in 1938, predominantly affects women, and leaves no trace on any standard cardiac risk assessment. What it does is compromise the structural integrity of the vessel wall — quietly, for years, sometimes for decades — creating the conditions for a spontaneous tear under physiological stress. A hard workout. A difficult labor. A prolonged period of grief.</p>
  <p>Researchers have now identified shared genetic variants between FMD and SCAD, including a variant in the PHACTR1 gene linked to both conditions. The biology is documented and real. It is also entirely invisible to the standard ER workup. A woman can carry this predisposition across her entire adult life, run half-marathons, raise children, pass every routine physical, and arrive one day at an emergency department struggling to breathe — and nothing in the checklist will flag her.</p>
  <p>The AHA now recommends that all SCAD patients be screened for FMD once in their lifetime. As of recent data, complete screening remains rare.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Everything I learned about SCAD in my medical training was wrong." — Dr. Sharonne Hayes</p></aside>

<section id="what-diagnosis-requires" class="reveal">
  <h2>The diagnosis no one orders</h2>
  <p>Confirming SCAD requires coronary angiography — threading a catheter into the coronary arteries to visualize the vessel walls directly. This is not a routine step when the attending has anchored on anxiety. It requires, as the AHA statement says plainly, a high index of suspicion for a condition that defies the classical cardiac profile. In practice, that means a physician who has genuinely internalized SCAD as a possibility — not one who read a statement once.</p>
  <p>Even angiography has limits. SCAD can mimic atherosclerotic disease on standard angiographic images; intravascular imaging — optical coherence tomography, intravascular ultrasound — visualizes the vessel wall in greater detail and catches what angiography alone might miss. These technologies exist and their use is growing. But they are deployed only when SCAD is suspected, which returns us to the original problem. The European Society of Cardiology has developed formal assessment pathways for myocardial infarction with non-obstructive coronary arteries — a category that includes SCAD — specifically to address what the old protocols miss. Dr. Malissa Wood at Massachusetts General Hospital, a co-author of the 2018 AHA statement, has been among those pressing for earlier angiographic investigation in young women presenting with acute coronary syndrome symptoms. The pathways are the field's best current answer to a structural problem. They are not yet uniformly applied.</p>
</section>

<section id="recurrence" class="reveal">
  <h2>It can happen again</h2>
  <p>Surviving SCAD is not the same as being cured. Recurrent dissection occurs in an estimated ten to thirty percent of patients over the following decade. The psychological aftermath is substantial: anxiety and depression are common among SCAD survivors, which creates a specific, cruel irony — anxiety is also what many of them were told they had in the first place. A misdiagnosis that generates the very symptom it invoked as explanation.</p>
  <p>Long-term management of SCAD remains incompletely defined. There are no randomized controlled trials — the patient population is specific, events are unpredictable, and the condition has only recently been taken seriously enough to generate prospective data. What is established: beta-blockers appear helpful; high-intensity competitive exercise is discouraged in recovery; cardiac rehabilitation tailored to SCAD's distinct physiology — not the standard post-MI protocol — is recommended; pregnancy after SCAD carries real risk and requires individualized counseling. The standard post-MI protocol, applied without adjustment to a SCAD survivor, is itself a problem the AHA statement specifically flags. Knowing about it and adjusting for it remain different things.</p>
</section>

<div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>What the numbers show</strong></p><p>SCAD accounts for approximately one-third of all heart attacks in women under fifty (npj Cardiovascular Health, 2024). It is the leading cause of pregnancy-associated myocardial infarction. Over ninety percent of patients are female, with a typical presentation age of forty-five to fifty-three. Fibromuscular dysplasia is identified in roughly seventy percent of patients in cohorts using comprehensive imaging. None of the classical cardiovascular risk factors — smoking, diabetes, high cholesterol, obesity — reliably predict it. The AHA has issued formal diagnostic and management guidance since 2018. Misdiagnosis remains common.</p></div>

<section id="what-doesnt-change" class="reveal">
  <h2>The gap between knowing and doing</h2>
  <p>The knowledge is not hidden. Dr. Hayes is a professor of cardiovascular medicine at Mayo Clinic who chairs the AHA writing group on SCAD. Dr. Wood is at Massachusetts General Hospital and helped write the consensus statement that defines the field. The research exists. The institutional authority exists. The diagnostic pathways exist.</p>
  <p>What does not exist, reliably, is the moment in the emergency department when a triage nurse sees a young woman with trouble breathing and the thought surfaces: this could be her heart. When the ECG returns subtle and the attending thinks: subtle changes in SCAD are real changes. When the troponin comes back borderline and the differential includes coronary dissection alongside panic attack. That cognitive shift — from "she's probably anxious" to "she might be dissecting" — is not produced by publishing a paper. It requires something harder: changing what medicine assumes by default about whose body is at cardiac risk.</p>
  <p>Those changes are slow. Slower than the rate at which young women are walking into ERs with tearing arteries and walking out with a referral to therapy.</p>
  <p>The attending physician who reaches for anxiety isn't corrupt. He is operating precisely as his training designed him to. That is the problem — not a bad actor, but a system optimized for the wrong patient, generating the wrong answer reliably and in good faith. The failure is diffuse, structural, and quiet.</p>
  <p>Which is, in its own way, worse than a scandal. Scandals end.</p>
</section>

